  "prompt": "When you look at yourself in the mirror, is the reality of what other people see greater or worse than what you see?",
  "response": "The perception of oneself in the mirror can vary greatly from person to person and is influenced by factors like self-esteem, body image, and societal standards of beauty. Many people tend to have a more critical view of themselves than what others see. This discrepancy can lead to feelings of inadequacy or self-doubt. Others might have a more favorable view of themselves, especially if they have a strong sense of self-confidence. Ultimately, the reality of how others perceive us can differ from our own self-image, and this can be shaped by personal experiences, relationships, and cultural influences.",
